  "prompt": "What is the difference between cheese, butter and ghee, paneer?",
  "response": "Here's a breakdown of the differences between cheese, butter, ghee, and paneer:\n\n1. Cheese:\n- Made from milk by curdling and processing\n- Many varieties with different textures and flavors\n- Can be soft or hard\n- Comes from various animal milks (cow, goat, sheep)\n- Usually contains cultures and enzymes\n- Can be aged or fresh\n\n2. Butter:\n- Made by churning cream or milk\n- High fat content (around 80%)\n- Spreadable at room temperature\n- Used in cooking and baking\n- Typically made from cow's milk\n- Solid at room temperature\n\n3. Ghee:\n- Clarified butter from cow's milk\n- Milk solids and water removed through heating\n- Higher smoke point than butter\n- Used in Indian cuisine\n- Golden color\n- Can be stored at room temperature\n- Lactose and casein-free\n\n4. Paneer:\n- Fresh Indian cheese\n- Made by curdling milk with acid (lemon juice or vinegar)\n- Soft, unaged cheese\n- No melting properties\n- High protein content\n- Vegetarian\n- Commonly used in Indian cooking\n- Mild flavor\n\nEach has unique characteristics and culinary uses.",
